treat that as some kind of RCU pointer.<br /><br />Adding a<br /><br />        grep -i rcu<br /><br />to the above shows that we have a couple of places that do this<br />carefully, but they are the exception rather than the rule.<br /><br />I think the issue is that "current-&gt;sighand" is always safe (and that<br />"me-&gt;sighand" is the same thing), and that sighand has RCU-delayed<br />freeing so that __lock_task_sighand() can safely try to take the lock<br />of another process' sighand.<br /><br />And we have no real way to explain to sparse that *some* cases are<br />fine, others are not and need the sighand lock (after that careful<br />__lock_task_sighand thing).<br /><br />              Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
